_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Poland"}
{"title_page": "Otak-otak", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Otak-otak\n| image            = Otak-otak Jakarta.JPG\n| image_size       = 230px\n| caption          = Otak-otak served in Jakarta\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Indonesia]]<ref name=\"MI-Otak-otak\">{{Cite news|url=https://mediaindonesia.com/read/detail/142346-otak-otak-makanan-favorit-semua-kalangan|title=Otak-Otak, Makanan Favorit Semua Kalangan|last=Ferdiansyah|first=Rendy|date=2018-01-25|website=Media Indonesia|language=id|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n| region           = Nationwide in Indonesia, and [[Malaysia]], [[Singapore]], [[Brunei]]\n| national_cuisine = [[Indonesian cuisine|Indonesia]], [[Malaysian cuisine|Malaysia]], [[Singaporean cuisine|Singapore]]\n| creator          =\n| course           = \n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = Fish meat, spices, leek, wrapped with banana leaf\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n\n'''''Otak-otak''''' is a grilled [[fish cake]] made of ground [[Fish (food)|fish meat]] mixed with [[tapioca]] starch and spices.<ref name=\"Eats\">{{cite web | title=Otak-Otak Bakar Recipe (Indonesian Grilled Fish Cake) | author=Peppy Nasution | publisher=Indonesia Eats | date=27 April 2011 | url=http://indonesiaeats.com/otak-otak-bakar-indonesian-grilled-fish-cake/ | accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref> It is widely known across Southeast Asia, especially in [[Indonesia]],<ref name=\"CNNGo\">{{cite web | title=40 of Indonesia's best dishes | author=Sara Schonhardt | publisher=CNN| date=15 August 2011 | url=http://travel.cnn.com/explorations/eat/40-foods-indonesians-cant-live-without-327106 | accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref> Malaysia and Singapore, where it is traditionally served fresh, wrapped inside a [[banana leaf]], as well as in many Asian stores internationally \u2013 being sold as frozen food. It can be eaten solely as a snack or with [[steamed rice]] as part of a meal.\n\n''Otak'' means \"brains\" in [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] and [[Malay language|Malay]], and the name of the dish is derived from the idea that the dish somewhat resembles brains, being whitish grey, soft and almost squishy.<ref name=\"Eats\"/>\nNevertheless, only the Indonesian otak-otak has whitish colour, while the otak-otak from Malaysia and Singapore has reddish-orange or brown colouring acquired from chili, turmeric and curry powder.\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Otak-Otak-Makassar.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Otak-otak in [[Makassar]], Indonesia ]]\n[[File:Penjual otak-otak menuang sambal kacang.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Otak-otak seller pouring spicy peanut sauce.]]\n[[File:YosriOtakOtak.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Grilling otak-otak in Malaysia ]]\n[[File:OTAK.jpg|right|thumb|The welknown [[Otak-otak]] of [[Muar (town)|Muar]], Johor, Malaysia available at the street.]]\n[[File:Katong otak otak.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Otak-otak from Katong, Singapore. Otak-otaks in Malaysia and Singapore are reddish.]]\n\nOtak-otak is found in certain parts of Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore. In Indonesia, three cities are famous for their otak-otak; [[Palembang]], [[Jakarta]] and [[Makassar]],<ref name=\"Eats\"/> nevertheless most of coastal fishing towns in Indonesia are familiar with this dish. \nOn the [[Bangka]] island, the town of [[Belinyu]] is famous as a production center of otak-otak.<ref name=\"MI-Otak-otak\"/>\n\nThe southern Malaysian town of [[Muar (town)|Muar]] in Johor is a popular destination for it \u2013 people from surrounding states and even Singaporeans often visit to buy the famous otak-otak in bulk.<ref name=Muar>{{cite web | title=Muar's matchless 'otak-otak' | author=Malaysia Tourism & Travel Guide |work= [[New Straits Times|NST]]| publisher=Tour Malaysia.com | url=http://www.tourmalaysia.com/malaysia-tourism/muars-matchless-otak-otak/  | accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> It is commonly known in Singapore as ''otah''.\n\n==Composition==\nOtak-otak is made by mixing [[fish paste]] with a mixture of spices. The type of fish used to make otak-otak might vary, [[mackerel]] is commonly used in Malaysia, while ''ikan tenggiri'' ([[wahoo]]) is popular ingredient in Indonesia. Other types of fish such as ''bandeng'' ([[milkfish]]) and the more expensive ''ikan belida'' ([[featherback]] fish) might be used.<ref name=\"Eats\"/> The ground fish and starch is seasoned with spices which usually includes garlic, [[shallot]], [[coconut milk]], pepper, salt and sugar.\n\nIn Indonesia, the mixture typically contains [[fish paste]], [[shallot]]s, garlic, [[scallion]]s, [[egg (food)|egg]], [[coconut milk]], and [[sago]] starch or can be substituted for [[tapioca]] starch. In Malaysia, it is usually a mixture between [[fish paste]], [[chili pepper]]s, garlic, [[shallot]]s, [[turmeric]], [[lemon grass]] and [[coconut milk]]. The mixture is then wrapped in a banana leaf that has been softened by steaming, then grilled or steamed.<ref>[http://www.tourism.terengganu.gov.my/culinary/otak-otak.htm Otak-otak.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203025412/http://tourism.terengganu.gov.my/culinary/otak-otak.htm |date=3 February 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn Jakarta, Indonesia, one finds otak-otak being sold in small stalls near bus stops, especially during afternoon rush hour. Some of the best otak-otak can be found in Makassar; the main ingredient is fresh king mackerel fish, also called king fish or [[spanish mackerel]].\n\nIn Malaysia Otak-otak is well-known and commonly found in a town called [[Muar (town)|Muar]], Johor located south of West Peninsular Malaysia. The otak-otak from Muar is particularly renowned in Malaysia.<ref name=Muar/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.malaysiabest.my/?p=4884 |title=ONE OF The Best Muar Traditional Authentic Food Taken Famously \"Otak-otak\", been Practiced bt Locals More Than a Decade|work= malaysiabest.my|publisher=Malaysia Best |date=14 October 2014|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref> The Muar's Otak-otak is extra-ordinary being wrapped inside the mangrove ''attap'' (''[[Nipa palm]]'') leaves and clipped using stapler or toothpick at both ends before being grilled or roasted on the stove.<ref name=Muar/> The flavor combines the fragrance of burnt ''attap'' leaves, the softness of fish meat and chili spices. The degree of spiciness corresponds to the amount of chilies being used. Since otak-otak is boneless fishcake, it is also suitable for children. While fish otak-otak is most common, otak-otak is also made with prawns, often resulting in a more textured variety. In Muar, there is also otak-otak made from [[cuttlefish]], shrimp, crab meat, fish head and even [[Chicken (food)|chicken]].<ref name=Muar/> Other than grilling in wrapped ''attap'' leaves, otak-otak might be conveniently and directly steamed instead.<ref name=Muar/> Steamed otak-otak is in rectangular shape without any attap leaves wrapping. Otak-otak are served best freshly hot, as a side dish with rice or as snacks during tea time.\n\n==Regional varieties==\nThere are different recipes of otak-otak originating from different regions.\n\nIn Indonesia, otak-otak commonly associated with [[Palembang]], South [[Sumatra]].<ref name=\"CNNGo\"/> However, other regions in Indonesia also popular for their otak-otak recipes, such as [[Jakarta]] and [[Makassar]]. In Palembang, people eat otak-otak with ''cuko'' ([[Palembang]]ese sweet and sour spicy vinegar sauce), while accross the strait on [[Bangka Belitung]] islands, the slightly different sour ''cuko'' sauce is made with a mixture of vinegar, shrimp paste and [[tauco]] fermented soybean paste.<ref name=\"MI-Otak-otak\"/> In Jakarta however, they enjoy it with spicy [[peanut sauce]].<ref name=\"CNNGo\"/> \n\nMalaysian Nyonya otak-otak (Malay: ''otak-otak Nyonya''), with [[Peranakan]] origins, from the northern Malaysian state of [[Penang]], is steamed as a cake in [[banana leaf]]. The otak-otak from Indonesia, the south of Malaysia, and Singapore is wrapped up as a thin slice using banana or coconut leaf and grilled over a charcoal fire. As a result, it ends up drier and with a more distinct smoky fish aroma. The colour of otak-otak from Indonesia is whitish, while the otak-otak from Malaysia and Singapore is reddish-orange. Other varieties of otak-otak do exist. Although otak-otak is traditionally made with fish meat, modern versions of otak may use [[Crab meat|crab]] or [[prawn]] meat or even fish head.\n\n== Similar dishes ==\nA type of delicacy similar to otak-otak from [[Terengganu]] is called [[Sata (food)|Sata]]. A similar Indonesian dish employing banana leaf is called [[pepes]]. Other types of otak-otak include dishes called ''pais ikan'', ''[[botok]]'' that are made of fish paste cooked in banana leaves. Otak-otak is quite similar to [[Szczecin paprikas]] ({{lang-pl|Paprykarz szczeci\u0144ski}}). \n\nThe Philippines has a similar delicacy called ''[[tupig]]'', which is cooked in the same manner as otak-otak \u2013 albeit the former is a sweet version. A thick batter made of glutinous rice flour (known locally as ''galapong'') coconut strips, coconut milk, sugar and nuts is wrapped in banana leaves, and then grilled over coals. ''Tupig'' is a well-known delicacy in the northern Philippine province of [[Pangasinan]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Food|Indonesia|Malaysia|Singapore}}\n* [[Palembang cuisine]]\n* [[Peranakan cuisine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Otak-otak}}\n* [http://indonesiancuisinerecipe.wordpress.com/2011/12/28/otak-otak-fish-cake-grilled-in-banana-leaves/ Otak-otak Jakarta recipe]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080302144928/http://kuali.com/recipes/viewrecipe.asp?r=767 Otak-Otak Recipe]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100203025412/http://tourism.terengganu.gov.my/culinary/otak-otak.htm Terengganu government tourism \u2013 Otak-otak.]\n\n{{Indonesian cuisine}}\n{{Malaysian cuisine}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Indonesian snack foods]]\n[[Category:Singaporean cuisine]]\n[[Category:Indonesian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Malaysian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Muar District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Otak-otak\n| image            = Otak-otak Jakarta.JPG\n| image_size       = 230px\n| caption          = Otak-otak served in Jakarta\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Indonesia]]<ref name=\"MI-Otak-otak\"><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mediaindonesia.com/read/detail/142346-otak-otak-makanan-favorit-semua-kalangan|title=Otak-Otak, Makanan Favorit Semua Kalangan|last=Ferdiansyah|first=Rendy|date=2018-01-25|website=Media Indonesia|language=id|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n| region           = Nationwide in Indonesia, and [[Malaysia]], [[Singapore]], [[Brunei]]\n| national_cuisine = [[Indonesian cuisine|Indonesia]], [[Malaysian cuisine|Malaysia]], [[Singaporean cuisine|Singapore]]\n| creator          =\n| course           = \n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = Fish meat, spices, leek, wrapped with banana leaf\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n\n'''''Otak-otak''''' is a grilled [[fish cake]] made of ground [[Fish (food)|fish meat]] mixed with [[tapioca]] starch and spices.<ref name=\"Eats\">{{cite web | title=Otak-Otak Bakar Recipe (Indonesian Grilled Fish Cake) | author=Peppy Nasution | publisher=Indonesia Eats | date=27 April 2011 | url=http://indonesiaeats.com/otak-otak-bakar-indonesian-grilled-fish-cake/ | accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref> It is widely known across Southeast Asia, especially in [[Indonesia]],<ref name=\"CNNGo\">{{cite web | title=40 of Indonesia's best dishes | author=Sara Schonhardt | publisher=CNN| date=15 August 2011 | url=http://travel.cnn.com/explorations/eat/40-foods-indonesians-cant-live-without-327106 | accessdate=4 September 2014}}</ref> Malaysia and Singapore, where it is traditionally served fresh, wrapped inside a [[banana leaf]], as well as in many Asian stores internationally \u2013 being sold as frozen food. It can be eaten solely as a snack or with [[steamed rice]] as part of a meal.\n\n''Otak'' means \"brains\" in [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]] and [[Malay language|Malay]], and the name of the dish is derived from the idea that the dish somewhat resembles brains, being whitish grey, soft and almost squishy.<ref name=\"Eats\"/>\nNevertheless, only the Indonesian otak-otak has whitish colour, while the otak-otak from Malaysia and Singapore has reddish-orange or brown colouring acquired from chili, turmeric and curry powder.\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Otak-Otak-Makassar.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Otak-otak in [[Makassar]], Indonesia ]]\n[[File:Penjual otak-otak menuang sambal kacang.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Otak-otak seller pouring spicy peanut sauce.]]\n[[File:YosriOtakOtak.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Grilling otak-otak in Malaysia ]]\n[[File:OTAK.jpg|right|thumb|The welknown [[Otak-otak]] of [[Muar (town)|Muar]], Johor, Malaysia available at the street.]]\n[[File:Katong otak otak.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Otak-otak from Katong, Singapore. Otak-otaks in Malaysia and Singapore are reddish.]]\n\nOtak-otak is found in certain parts of Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore. In Indonesia, three cities are famous for their otak-otak; [[Palembang]], [[Jakarta]] and [[Makassar]],<ref name=\"Eats\"/> nevertheless most of coastal fishing towns in Indonesia are familiar with this dish. \nOn the [[Bangka]] island, the town of [[Belinyu]] is famous as a production center of otak-otak.<ref name=\"MI-Otak-otak\"/>\n\nThe southern Malaysian town of [[Muar (town)|Muar]] in Johor is a popular destination for it \u2013 people from surrounding states and even Singaporeans often visit to buy the famous otak-otak in bulk.<ref name=Muar>{{cite web | title=Muar's matchless 'otak-otak' | author=Malaysia Tourism & Travel Guide |work= [[New Straits Times|NST]]| publisher=Tour Malaysia.com | url=http://www.tourmalaysia.com/malaysia-tourism/muars-matchless-otak-otak/  | accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> It is commonly known in Singapore as ''otah''.\n\n==Composition==\nOtak-otak is made by mixing [[fish paste]] with a mixture of spices. The type of fish used to make otak-otak might vary, [[mackerel]] is commonly used in Malaysia, while ''ikan tenggiri'' ([[wahoo]]) is popular ingredient in Indonesia. Other types of fish such as ''bandeng'' ([[milkfish]]) and the more expensive ''ikan belida'' ([[featherback]] fish) might be used.<ref name=\"Eats\"/> The ground fish and starch is seasoned with spices which usually includes garlic, [[shallot]], [[coconut milk]], pepper, salt and sugar.\n\nIn Indonesia, the mixture typically contains [[fish paste]], [[shallot]]s, garlic, [[scallion]]s, [[egg (food)|egg]], [[coconut milk]], and [[sago]] starch or can be substituted for [[tapioca]] starch. In Malaysia, it is usually a mixture between [[fish paste]], [[chili pepper]]s, garlic, [[shallot]]s, [[turmeric]], [[lemon grass]] and [[coconut milk]]. The mixture is then wrapped in a banana leaf that has been softened by steaming, then grilled or steamed.<ref>[http://www.tourism.terengganu.gov.my/culinary/otak-otak.htm Otak-otak.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100203025412/http://tourism.terengganu.gov.my/culinary/otak-otak.htm |date=3 February 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn Jakarta, Indonesia, one finds otak-otak being sold in small stalls near bus stops, especially during afternoon rush hour. Some of the best otak-otak can be found in Makassar; the main ingredient is fresh king mackerel fish, also called king fish or [[spanish mackerel]].\n\nIn Malaysia Otak-otak is well-known and commonly found in a town called [[Muar (town)|Muar]], Johor located south of West Peninsular Malaysia. The otak-otak from Muar is particularly renowned in Malaysia.<ref name=Muar/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.malaysiabest.my/?p=4884 |title=ONE OF The Best Muar Traditional Authentic Food Taken Famously \"Otak-otak\", been Practiced bt Locals More Than a Decade|work= malaysiabest.my|publisher=Malaysia Best |date=14 October 2014|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref> The Muar's Otak-otak is extra-ordinary being wrapped inside the mangrove ''attap'' (''[[Nipa palm]]'') leaves and clipped using stapler or toothpick at both ends before being grilled or roasted on the stove.<ref name=Muar/> The flavor combines the fragrance of burnt ''attap'' leaves, the softness of fish meat and chili spices. The degree of spiciness corresponds to the amount of chilies being used. Since otak-otak is boneless fishcake, it is also suitable for children. While fish otak-otak is most common, otak-otak is also made with prawns, often resulting in a more textured variety. In Muar, there is also otak-otak made from [[cuttlefish]], shrimp, crab meat, fish head and even [[Chicken (food)|chicken]].<ref name=Muar/> Other than grilling in wrapped ''attap'' leaves, otak-otak might be conveniently and directly steamed instead.<ref name=Muar/> Steamed otak-otak is in rectangular shape without any attap leaves wrapping. Otak-otak are served best freshly hot, as a side dish with rice or as snacks during tea time.\n\n==Regional varieties==\nThere are different recipes of otak-otak originating from different regions.\n\nIn Indonesia, otak-otak commonly associated with [[Palembang]], South [[Sumatra]].<ref name=\"CNNGo\"/> However, other regions in Indonesia also popular for their otak-otak recipes, such as [[Jakarta]] and [[Makassar]]. In Palembang, people eat otak-otak with ''cuko'' ([[Palembang]]ese sweet and sour spicy vinegar sauce), while accross the strait on [[Bangka Belitung]] islands, the slightly different sour ''cuko'' sauce is made with a mixture of vinegar, shrimp paste and [[tauco]] fermented soybean paste.<ref name=\"MI-Otak-otak\"/> In Jakarta however, they enjoy it with spicy [[peanut sauce]].<ref name=\"CNNGo\"/> \n\nMalaysian Nyonya otak-otak (Malay: ''otak-otak Nyonya''), with [[Peranakan]] origins, from the northern Malaysian state of [[Penang]], is steamed as a cake in [[banana leaf]]. The otak-otak from Indonesia, the south of Malaysia, and Singapore is wrapped up as a thin slice using banana or coconut leaf and grilled over a charcoal fire. As a result, it ends up drier and with a more distinct smoky fish aroma. The colour of otak-otak from Indonesia is whitish, while the otak-otak from Malaysia and Singapore is reddish-orange. Other varieties of otak-otak do exist. Although otak-otak is traditionally made with fish meat, modern versions of otak may use [[Crab meat|crab]] or [[prawn]] meat or even fish head.\n\n== Similar dishes ==\nA type of delicacy similar to otak-otak from [[Terengganu]] is called [[Sata (food)|Sata]]. A similar Indonesian dish employing banana leaf is called [[pepes]]. Other types of otak-otak include dishes called ''pais ikan'', ''[[botok]]'' that are made of fish paste cooked in banana leaves. Otak-otak is quite similar to [[Szczecin paprikas]] ({{lang-pl|Paprykarz szczeci\u0144ski}}). \n\nThe Philippines has a similar delicacy called ''[[tupig]]'', which is cooked in the same manner as otak-otak \u2013 albeit the former is a sweet version. A thick batter made of glutinous rice flour (known locally as ''galapong'') coconut strips, coconut milk, sugar and nuts is wrapped in banana leaves, and then grilled over coals. ''Tupig'' is a well-known delicacy in the northern Philippine province of [[Pangasinan]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Food|Indonesia|Malaysia|Singapore}}\n* [[Palembang cuisine]]\n* [[Peranakan cuisine]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Otak-otak}}\n* [http://indonesiancuisinerecipe.wordpress.com/2011/12/28/otak-otak-fish-cake-grilled-in-banana-leaves/ Otak-otak Jakarta recipe]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080302144928/http://kuali.com/recipes/viewrecipe.asp?r=767 Otak-Otak Recipe]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100203025412/http://tourism.terengganu.gov.my/culinary/otak-otak.htm Terengganu government tourism \u2013 Otak-otak.]\n\n{{Indonesian cuisine}}\n{{Malaysian cuisine}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Indonesian snack foods]]\n[[Category:Singaporean cuisine]]\n[[Category:Indonesian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Malaysian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Muar District]]\n", "name_user": "Gunkarta", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Otak-otak"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Vatican City", "text_new": "{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Vatican City}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Vatican City\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Vatican City]]\n| arrival_date    = 5 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=5|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| date            = {{as of|2020|April|2}}\n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 7\n| suspected_cases = \n| website         = \n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Vatican City]] in March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/03/06/news/toscana_contagiata_una_bimba_di_45_giorni-250393465/|title=Coronavirus, primo caso in Vaticano. In Toscana contagiata una bimba di 45 giorni|date=6 March 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> There are 7 confirmed cases of COVID-19 and no associated deaths.\n\nDue to Vatican City's small population of 618 people at the time of the outbreak,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vaticanstate.va/it/stato-governo/note-generali/popolazione.html|title=Popolazione|website=www.vaticanstate.va|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> the country's 7 cases give it a case per capita percentage of 1.1%; the highest of all states in the world.\n\n[[Pope Francis]] became ill with symptoms of a [[Common cold|cold]], but tested negative for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pope-health/pope-tests-negative-for-coronavirus-italy-report-says-idUSKBN20Q0K0 |title=Pope tests negative for coronavirus, Italy report says |first1=Giselda |last1=Vagnoni |first2=Philip |last2=Pullella |date=3 March 2020 |website=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n==Preventive measures==\nItaly's lockdown measures have been mirrored in Vatican City. As such, tourist attractions have been closed. To reduce public gatherings and transmission of the virus, Pope Francis cancelled his regular appearances in public and will livestream them on the internet instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-pope/pope-cancels-main-public-appearances-to-stop-crowds-gathering-amid-coronavirus-idUSKBN20U0JH |title=Pope cancels main public appearances to stop crowds gathering amid coronavirus |first=Philip |last=Pullella |date=7 March 2020 |website=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Vatican City medical cases chart}}\n\n===March===\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to Vatican City on 5 March 2020, with one case.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Jordan|last1=Kelly-Linden|first2=Global Health Security|last2=Team|accessdate=2020-03-06|title=Coronavirus latest news: Vatican City reports first case|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-uk-news-cases-latest-update-covid-19-live/|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=6 March 2020|issn=0307-1235|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Reuters|accessdate=2020-03-06|title=Vatican Reports First Case of Coronavirus Inside Its Walls|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/06/world/europe/06reuters-health-coronavirus-vatican.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=6 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 8 March [[Angelus]] was offered via [[Streaming media|livestreaming]] from the Pope's private library.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Euronews|accessdate=2020-03-14|title=Pope Francis voices support for coronavirus victims in livestream message|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/03/08/pope-francis-voices-support-for-coronavirus-victims-in-livestream-message|date=8 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Vatican Museums]] have been shut down from 8 March to 3 April.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Catholic News Agency|accessdate=2020-03-14|title=Vatican Museums closed until April 3|url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/vatican-museums-closed-until-april-3-31614|date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, after the [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|lockdown in Italy]], [[Saint Peter's Square]] and [[St. Peter's Basilica]] were closed to tourists between 10 March and 3 April. Italy's lockdown measures are also applied to the Vatican City.<ref>{{cite news|last1=The Guardian|accessdate=2020-03-14|title=St Peter's Square before and after Italy's coronavirus lockdown \u2013 video|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2020/mar/10/st-peters-square-before-and-after-italys-nationwide-lockdown-videon|date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, the Pope offered a virtual general audience for the first time.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reuters|accessdate=2020-03-14|title=Pope holds his first ever virtual general audience with Italy on lockdown|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-cornavirus-pope/pope-holds-his-first-ever-virtual-general-audience-with-italy-on-lockdown-idUSKBN20Y1M2|date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, Francis prayed at [[San Marcello al Corso]] in [[Rome]] before a crucifix which is regarded by Catholics as miraculous, and was carried in [[procession]] during the [[Miraculous plague cure of 1522|plague of 1522]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/pope-francis-makes-walking-prayer-pilgrimage-for-coronavirus-pandemic|title=Pope Francis Makes Walking Prayer Pilgrimage for Coronavirus Pandemic|website=National Catholic Register|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, three more cases were confirmed in Vatican City, bringing the total to four cases, one of which was a high-ranking [[prelate]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilmessaggero.it/vaticano/coronavirus_vaticano_papa_francesco_casi_contagi_curia_comunicato_uffici_amuchina-5130705.html|title=Il Vaticano non chiude gli uffici \"allo scopo di evitare il contagio\": la gaffe nel comunicato, 4 i positivi|website=Il Messaggero|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March Pope Francis delivered a special ''[[Urbi et Orbi]]'' blessing in an empty Saint Peter's Square praying for the end of coronavirus pandemic, before the San Marcello al Corso's miraculous crucifix that was moved from its original church in Rome two days ago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vaticannews.va/en/pope/news/2020-03/pope-francis-urbi-et-orbi-blessing-coronavirus.html|title=Pope's special Urbi et Orbi blessing: 'God turns everything to our good'|website=Vatican News|date=27 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aleteia.org/2020/03/26/miraculous-crucifix-from-1522-plague-moved-to-st-peters-for-popes-urbi-et-orbi-blessing/|title=Miraculous crucifix from 1522 plague moved to St. Peter's for pope's 'Urbi et Orbi' blessing|website=[[Aleteia]]|date=26 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, two more cases were confirmed in Vatican City, bringing the total to six cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vaticannews.va/en/vatican-city/news/2020-03/coronavirus-pope-positive-vatican-santa-marta-holy-see.html|title=Covid-19: 2 new cases in the Vatican, another 170 people tested - Vatican News|date=2020-03-28|website=www.vaticannews.va|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn 2 April, another case was confirmed in Vatican City, bringing the total to seven cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ansa.it/english/news/vatican/2020/04/02/coronavirus-vatican-reports-7th-case-2_710a8291-356b-4f3f-8e49-c8e37e9f789f.html|title=Coronavirus: Vatican reports 7th case (2) - English|date=2020-04-02|website=ANSA.it|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Vatican City|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Vatican City]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Vatican City]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Vatican City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Vatican City}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Vatican City\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Vatican City]]\n| arrival_date    = 5 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=5|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| date            = {{as of|2020|April|2}}\n| recovery_cases  = \n| deaths          = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 7\n| suspected_cases = \n| website         = \n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Vatican City]] in March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/03/06/news/toscana_contagiata_una_bimba_di_45_giorni-250393465/|title=Coronavirus, primo caso in Vaticano. In Toscana contagiata una bimba di 45 giorni|date=6 March 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> There are 7 confirmed cases of COVID-19 and no associated deaths.\n\nDue to Vatican City's small population of 618 people at the time of the outbreak,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vaticanstate.va/it/stato-governo/note-generali/popolazione.html|title=Popolazione|website=www.vaticanstate.va|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> the country's 7 cases give it a case per capita percentage of 1.1%; the highest of all states in the world.\n\n[[Pope Francis]] became ill with symptoms of a [[Common cold|cold]], but tested negative for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pope-health/pope-tests-negative-for-coronavirus-italy-report-says-idUSKBN20Q0K0 |title=Pope tests negative for coronavirus, Italy report says |first1=Giselda |last1=Vagnoni |first2=Philip |last2=Pullella |date=3 March 2020 |website=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n==Preventive measures==\nItaly's lockdown measures have been mirrored in Vatican City. As such, tourist attractions have been closed. To reduce public gatherings and transmission of the virus, Pope Francis cancelled his regular appearances in public and will livestream them on the internet instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-pope/pope-cancels-main-public-appearances-to-stop-crowds-gathering-amid-coronavirus-idUSKBN20U0JH |title=Pope cancels main public appearances to stop crowds gathering amid coronavirus |first=Philip |last=Pullella |date=7 March 2020 |website=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Vatican City medical cases chart}}\n\n===March===\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to Vatican City on 5 March 2020, with one case.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Jordan|last1=Kelly-Linden|first2=Global Health Security|last2=Team|accessdate=2020-03-06|title=Coronavirus latest news: Vatican City reports first case|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/global-health/science-and-disease/coronavirus-uk-news-cases-latest-update-covid-19-live/|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=6 March 2020|issn=0307-1235|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Reuters|accessdate=2020-03-06|title=Vatican Reports First Case of Coronavirus Inside Its Walls|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/03/06/world/europe/06reuters-health-coronavirus-vatican.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=6 March 2020|issn=0362-4331|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 8 March [[Angelus]] was offered via [[Streaming media|livestreaming]] from the Pope's private library.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Euronews|accessdate=2020-03-14|title=Pope Francis voices support for coronavirus victims in livestream message|url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/03/08/pope-francis-voices-support-for-coronavirus-victims-in-livestream-message|date=8 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Vatican Museums]] have been shut down from 8 March to 3 April.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Catholic News Agency|accessdate=2020-03-14|title=Vatican Museums closed until April 3|url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/vatican-museums-closed-until-april-3-31614|date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, after the [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|lockdown in Italy]], [[Saint Peter's Square]] and [[St. Peter's Basilica]] were closed to tourists between 10 March and 3 April. Italy's lockdown measures are also applied to the Vatican City.<ref>{{cite news|last1=The Guardian|accessdate=2020-03-14|title=St Peter's Square before and after Italy's coronavirus lockdown \u2013 video|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2020/mar/10/st-peters-square-before-and-after-italys-nationwide-lockdown-videon|date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, the Pope offered a virtual general audience for the first time.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Reuters|accessdate=2020-03-14|title=Pope holds his first ever virtual general audience with Italy on lockdown|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-cornavirus-pope/pope-holds-his-first-ever-virtual-general-audience-with-italy-on-lockdown-idUSKBN20Y1M2|date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, Francis prayed at [[San Marcello al Corso]] in [[Rome]] before a crucifix which is regarded by Catholics as miraculous, and was carried in [[procession]] during the [[Miraculous plague cure of 1522|plague of 1522]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/pope-francis-makes-walking-prayer-pilgrimage-for-coronavirus-pandemic|title=Pope Francis Makes Walking Prayer Pilgrimage for Coronavirus Pandemic|website=National Catholic Register|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, three more cases were confirmed in Vatican City, bringing the total to four cases, one of which was a high-ranking [[prelate]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ilmessaggero.it/vaticano/coronavirus_vaticano_papa_francesco_casi_contagi_curia_comunicato_uffici_amuchina-5130705.html|title=Il Vaticano non chiude gli uffici \"allo scopo di evitare il contagio\": la gaffe nel comunicato, 4 i positivi|website=Il Messaggero|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March Pope Francis delivered a special [[Urbi et Orbi]] blessing in an empty Saint Peter's Square praying for the end of coronavirus pandemic, before the San Marcello al Corso's miraculous crucifix that was moved from its original church in Rome two days ago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vaticannews.va/en/pope/news/2020-03/pope-francis-urbi-et-orbi-blessing-coronavirus.html|title=Pope's special Urbi et Orbi blessing: 'God turns everything to our good'|website=Vatican News|date=27 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aleteia.org/2020/03/26/miraculous-crucifix-from-1522-plague-moved-to-st-peters-for-popes-urbi-et-orbi-blessing/|title=Miraculous crucifix from 1522 plague moved to St. Peter's for pope's 'Urbi et Orbi' blessing|website=[[Aleteia]]|date=26 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, two more cases were confirmed in Vatican City, bringing the total to six cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vaticannews.va/en/vatican-city/news/2020-03/coronavirus-pope-positive-vatican-santa-marta-holy-see.html|title=Covid-19: 2 new cases in the Vatican, another 170 people tested - Vatican News|date=2020-03-28|website=www.vaticannews.va|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn 2 April, another case was confirmed in Vatican City, bringing the total to seven cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ansa.it/english/news/vatican/2020/04/02/coronavirus-vatican-reports-7th-case-2_710a8291-356b-4f3f-8e49-c8e37e9f789f.html|title=Coronavirus: Vatican reports 7th case (2) - English|date=2020-04-02|website=ANSA.it|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Vatican City|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Vatican City]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Vatican City]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Vatican City]]\n", "name_user": "Ypna", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarch:italicise Latin", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Vatican_City"}
{"title_page": "Elizabeth Savage, Countess Rivers", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n'''Elizabeth Savage, Countess Rivers''' and '''Viscountess Savage''' (1581 \u2013 9 March 1650) was an [[Kingdom of England|English]] courtier and a [[Cavalier|Royalist]] victim of uprisings during the [[English Civil War]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn Hon. Elizabeth Darcy, she was the daughter of [[Thomas Darcy, 1st Earl Rivers]] and Mary Kitson (died 1644), a granddaughter of [[Thomas Kitson]].\n\n==Marriage==\nOn 14 May 1602, Elizabeth married [[Thomas Savage, 1st Viscount Savage|Thomas Savage]] and they had eleven sons and eight daughters. He was the eldest son of [[Sir John Savage, 1st Baronet]] and his wife Mary ''n\u00e9e'' Allington, from whom he inherited [[Melford Hall]] in [[Suffolk]]. In 1615, he inherited his father's baronetcy and was created [[Viscount Savage]] in 1626. On his death in 1635, Elizabeth (by now Viscountess Savage) inherited Melford. This and [[St Osyth Priory]] in [[Essex]] formed her principal residences.\n\nOn the death of Lady Savage's father in 1640, the earldom of Rivers passed to her eldest son, [[John Savage, 2nd Earl Rivers|John]]. As compensation for not enjoying the rank of a countess, she was created Countess Rivers [[Pre-1876 Life Peerages|for life]] in 1641.\n\n==Allegiances==\nAs well as inheriting property and being raised in rank following the death of her father and husband, she also inherited their political and religious allegiances that would later lead to her downfall in the [[English Civil War]]. Both men were closely associated with [[Charles I of England|Charles I]], had links with [[George Villiers, 2nd Duke of Buckingham]] and both had enforced the king's policies for Essex in the case of Lord Rivers and [[Lancashire]] and [[Cheshire]] in the case of Lord Savage. Lady Rivers and her husband had both served in [[Henrietta Maria of France|Queen Henrietta Maria]]'s court as a [[Lady of the Bedchamber]] and Chancellor respectively, due to the family's strong [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] links. Lady Rivers' father had been suspected of being a [[Papist]], but was protected against [[recusancy]] legislation, although he was excluded from the county [[magistrate|magistracy]].\n\n==Civil War==\nFollowing parliament's explanation of the ineffectual settlement with the king to have been caused by a Catholic conspiracy, local grievances heightened rumour and suspicion and Lady Rivers was presented to the Essex [[justices of the peace]] as a [[recusant]] and her home at St Osyth was searched for [[weapon|arms]]. Following the attack on [[John Lucas (royalist)|Sir John Lucas]] at [[Colchester]] during the [[Stour Valley riots]], St Osyth was ransacked and plundered by the crowds. Forewarned, Lady Rivers had fled to [[Long Melford]] but the crowds followed her there, attempting to also destroy that residence. According to a local story, Lady Rivers, upon also escaping Melford, threw a box with a string of [[pearl]]s into a nearby pond before fleeing.\n\n==Later life==\nAlthough attacked by the masses in opposition to her family's association with the king and their religious patronage, Lady Rivers secured support from those who did not share the same views. Parliament later ordered her estates to be restored to her, but her [[leasehold estate|tenants]] subsequently refused to pay [[renting|rent]]. After a second episode of invasion of her estates by Parliamentarian soldiers, she sought permission to go to [[France]] in May 1643. After her return, she successfully petitioned Parliament to have her estates restored again, but the attacks on them and the fines imposed upon her and her son left her penniless. On her death in 1651, she was said to have been bankrupt and was buried at St Osyth with her ancestors.\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''`Elizabeth Savage, Countess Rivers'''\n|2= 2. [[Thomas Darcy, 1st Earl Rivers]]\n|3= 3. Mary Kitson (-1644)\n|4= 4.  John, 2nd Lord Darcy of Chiche (-1580)\n|5= 5. Frances Rich\n|6= 6. Sir Thomas Kitson (1540-1604)\n|7= 7. Elizabeth Cornwallis\n|8= 8. [[Thomas Darcy, 1st Baron Darcy of Chiche|Thomas, 1st Lord Darcy]]\n|9= 9. Lady Elizabeth de Vere\n|10= 10. [[Richard Rich, 1st Baron Rich]]\n|11= 11. Elizabeth Jenks (-1558)\n|12= 12. Sir [[Thomas Kytson]]\n|13= 13. Margaret Donnington (-1561)\n|14= 14. Sir [[Thomas Cornwallis (died 1604)|Thomas Cornwallis]]\n|15= 15. Anne Jerningham (1523-81)\n|16= 16. Roger Darcy (-1508)\n|17= 17. Elizabeth Wentworth\n|18= 18. [[John de Vere, 15th Earl of Oxford]]\n|19= 19. [[Elizabeth de Vere, Countess of Oxford|Elizabeth Trussell]]\n|20= 20. John Rich\n|21=\n|22= 22. William Jenks\n|23= 23. Elizabeth Adams\n|24= 24. Robert Kitson\n|25= 25. Margaret Smith (-1588)\n|26= 26. John Donnington (-1544)\n|27= 27. Elizabeth Pye\n|28= 28. Sir John Cornwallis (1491-1544)\n|29= 29. Mary Sulyard\n|30= 30. Sir John Jerningham\n|31= 31. Elizabeth, daughter of [[Robert Drury (speaker)|Sir Robert Drury]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/69349 Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rivers, Elizabeth Savage, Countess}}\n[[Category:Daughters of British earls]]\n[[Category:English viscountesses]]\n[[Category:Pre-1876 life peers]]\n[[Category:1581 births]]\n[[Category:1650 deaths]]\n[[Category:Created suo jure peeresses]]\n[[Category:Peers of England created by Charles I]]\n[[Category:Cavaliers]]\n[[Category:English countesses]]\n[[Category:17th-century English women]]\n[[Category:17th-century English nobility]]\n[[Category:Women of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:People from Long Melford]]\n[[Category:Women in the English Civil War]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n'''Elizabeth Savage, Countess Rivers''' and '''Viscountess Savage''' (1581 \u2013 9 March 1650) was an [[Kingdom of England|English]] courtier and a [[Cavalier|Royalist]] victim of uprisings during the [[English Civil War]].\n\n==Early life==\nBorn Hon. Elizabeth Darcy, she was the daughter of [[Thomas Darcy, 1st Earl Rivers]] and Mary Kitson (died 1644), a granddaughter of [[Thomas Kitson]].\n\n==Marriage==\nOn 14 May 1602, Elizabeth married [[Thomas Savage, 1st Viscount Savage|Thomas Savage]] and they had eleven sons and eight daughters. He was the eldest son of [[Sir John Savage, 1st Baronet]] and his wife Mary ''n\u00e9e'' Allington, from whom he inherited [[Melford Hall]] in [[Suffolk]]. In 1615, he inherited his father's baronetcy and was created [[Viscount Savage]] in 1626. On his death in 1635, Elizabeth (by now Viscountess Savage) inherited Melford. This and [[St Osyth Priory]] in [[Essex]] formed her principal residences.\n\nOn death of Lady Savage's father in 1640, the earldom of Rivers passed to her eldest son, [[John Savage, 2nd Earl Rivers|John]]. As compensation for not enjoying the rank of a countess, she was created Countess Rivers [[Pre-1876 Life Peerages|for life]] in 1641.\n\n==Allegiances==\nAs well as inheriting property and being raised in rank following the death of her father and husband, she also inherited their political and religious allegiances that would later lead to her downfall in the [[English Civil War]]. Both men were closely associated with [[Charles I of England|Charles I]], had links with [[George Villiers, 2nd Duke of Buckingham]] and both had enforced the king's policies for Essex in the case of Lord Rivers and [[Lancashire]] and [[Cheshire]] in the case of Lord Savage. Lady Rivers and her husband had both served in [[Henrietta Maria of France|Queen Henrietta Maria]]'s court as a [[Lady of the Bedchamber]] and Chancellor respectively, due to the family's strong [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] links. Lady Rivers' father had been suspected of being a [[Papist]], but was protected against [[recusancy]] legislation, although he was excluded from the county [[magistrate|magistracy]].\n\n==Civil War==\nFollowing parliament's explanation of the ineffectual settlement with the king to have been caused by a Catholic conspiracy, local grievances heightened rumour and suspicion and Lady Rivers was presented to the Essex [[justices of the peace]] as a [[recusant]] and her home at St Osyth was searched for [[weapon|arms]]. Following the attack on [[John Lucas (royalist)|Sir John Lucas]] at [[Colchester]] during the [[Stour Valley riots]], St Osyth was ransacked and plundered by the crowds. Forewarned, Lady Rivers had fled to [[Long Melford]] but the crowds followed her there, attempting to also destroy that residence. According to a local story, Lady Rivers, upon also escaping Melford, threw a box with a string of [[pearl]]s into a nearby pond before fleeing.\n\n==Later life==\nAlthough attacked by the masses in opposition to her family's association with the king and their religious patronage, Lady Rivers secured support from those who did not share the same views. Parliament later ordered her estates to be restored to her, but her [[leasehold estate|tenants]] subsequently refused to pay [[renting|rent]]. After a second episode of invasion of her estates by Parliamentarian soldiers, she sought permission to go to [[France]] in May 1643. After her return, she successfully petitioned Parliament to have her estates restored again, but the attacks on them and the fines imposed upon her and her son left her penniless. On her death in 1651, she was said to have been bankrupt and was buried at St Osyth with her ancestors.\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 